formula: From n > 1 onward a(n) = A080237(A081291(n-1)). - _Antti Karttunen_, Jul 31 2003

A007007.name: Valence of graph of maximal intersecting families of sets.
formula: Equals A037952 except for n=1 [Loeb & Meyerowitz, theorem 16]. - _Andrey Zabolotskiy_, Sep 19 2017

A007008.name: Chvatal conjecture for radius of graph of maximal intersecting sets.
formula: It is conjectured that a(2n+1)=A000346(n-1) for n>0. - _Ralf Stephan_, May 03 2004
a(n)=round(2^(n-2)-binomial(n-1,floor((n-1)/2))/2), cf. Thm. 14 in the Loeb-Meyerowitz paper. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 14 2014

A007009.name: Number of 3-voter voting schemes with n linearly ranked choices.

A007010.name: Number of 4-voter voting schemes with n linearly ranked choices.

A007013.name: Catalan-Mersenne numbers: a(0) = 2; for n >= 0, a(n+1) = 2^a(n) - 1.
formula: a(n) = M(a(n-1)) = M^n(2) with M: n-> 2^n-1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 15 2006

A007015.name: a(n) = smallest k such that phi(n+k) = phi(k).

A007016.name: Number of permutations of length n with 1 fixed and 1 reflected point.

A007017.name: Number of motifs in triangular window of side n.

A007018.name: a(n) = a(n-1)^2 + a(n-1), a(0)=1.
formula: a(n) = A000058(n)-1 = A000058(n-1)^2 - A000058(n-1) = 1/(1-Sum_{j<n} 1/A000058(j)) where A000058 is Sylvester's sequence. - _Henry Bottomley_, Jul 23 2001
If an (additional) initial 1 is inserted, a(n) = Sum_{k<n} a(k)^2. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jun 11 2009
a(n+1) = a(n)-th oblong (or promic, pronic, or heteromecic) numbers (A002378). a(n+1) = A002378(a(n)) = A002378(a(n-1)) * (A002378(a(n-1)) + 1). - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Sep 13 2009

A007019.name: a(n) = (2n+1)! / 2^n.
formula: a(n) = Product_{j=1..n} T(2j) (where T(k) is the k-th triangular number). For example: a(3) = T(2)*T(4)*T(6) (that is, 630 = 3*10*21). - _Rigoberto Florez_, Aug 26 2018

A007039.name: Number of cyclic binary n-bit strings with no alternating substring of length > 2.
formula: For n >= 5, a(n) = 2a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-4). - _David W. Wilson_

A007040.name: Number of (marked) cyclic n-bit binary strings containing no runs of length > 2.
formula: a(n) = a(n-2) + 2*a(n-3) + a(n-4), n >= 7. - _David W. Wilson_
a(n) = n*Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(2*k, n-2*k)/k for n > 1 with a(0) = 0 and a(1) = 2. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Oct 12 2011
a(n) = A000032(n) + 2*cos(2*Pi*n/3) for n > 1. - _Eric W. Weisstein_, Mar 30 2017
a(n) = A000032(n) - A061347(n) for n > 1. - _Wojciech Florek_, Feb 18 2018

A007042.name: Left diagonal of partition triangle A047812.

A007043.name: Number of noncommutative SL(2,C)-invariants of degree n in 5 variables.
formula: a(n) ~ 5^n/(8*sqrt(Pi)*n^(3/2)) * (1 - 15/(16*n) + O(1/n^2)). - _Thomas Curtright_, Jun 17 2016, updated Jul 26 2016

A007044.name: Left diagonal of partition triangle A047812.

A007045.name: Second (lower) diagonal of partition triangle A047812.

A007046.name: Number of irreducible positions of size n in Montreal solitaire.
formula: a(n) = d(n, 2) where d(n, k) = 0 if n < k*(k+1)/2, d(n, k) = 1 if n = k*(k+1)/2, and d(n, k) = d(n, k+1) + Sum_{r=1..k} binomial(k + 1, r) * d(n - k*(k+1)/2 + r*(r-1)/2, r) if n > k*(k+1)/2 [From Cannings and Haigh]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Sep 25 2017

A007047.name: Number of chains in power set of n-set.
formula: a(n) = one less than sum of quotients with numerator 4 times (n!)((k_1 + k_2 + ... + k_n)!) and with denominator (k_1!k_2!...k_n!)(1!^k_1 2!^k_2...n!^k_n) where the sum is taken over all partitions 1*k_1 + 2*k_2 + ... + n*k_n = n. E.g. a(1) = 3 because the membership value of x to {x} is either 1, alpha with 0 < alpha < 1 or 0. a(2) = 11 since the membership values x and y to {x, y} are 1 >= alpha >= beta >= 0 for {empty set, x, y} in that order or {empty set, y, x} exercising all possible > or = . - Venkat Murali (v.murali(AT)ru.ac.za), May 18 2005
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - 3*x*(k+1) - 2*x^2*(k+1)*(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 02 2013
a(n) = 4 * A000670(n) - 1 for n > 0. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Feb 07 2020
a(n) = -(-1)^n Phi(2,-n,-1), where Phi(z,s,a) is the Lerch Zeta function. - _Federico Provvedi_, Sep 05 2020
a(n) = 1 + 2 * Sum_{k=0..n-1} (-1)^(n-k-1) * binomial(n,k) * a(k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 28 2021

A007048.name: Number of irreducible positions of size n in Montreal solitaire.

A007049.name: Number of irreducible positions of size n in Montreal solitaire.

A007051.name: a(n) = (3^n + 1)/2.
formula: Binomial transform of Chebyshev coefficients A011782. - _Paul Barry_, Mar 16 2003

This sequence is also the partial sums of the first 3 Stirling numbers of second kind: a(n) = S(n+1, 1) + S(n+1, 2) + S(n+1, 3) for n >= 0; alternatively it is the number of partitions of [n+1] into 3 or fewer parts. - _Mike Zabrocki_, Jun 21 2004
The i-th term of the sequence is the entry (1, 1) in the i-th power of the 2 X 2 matrix M = ((2, 1), (1, 2)). - _Simone Severini_, Oct 15 2005

If p[i]=fibonacci(2i-3) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)= det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010
INVERT transform of A001519: [1, 1, 2, 5, 13, 34, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 13 2011

a(n) = M^n*[1,1,1,0,0,0,...], leftmost column term; where M = an infinite bidiagonal matrix with all 1's in the superdiagonal and (1,2,3,...) in the main diagonal and the rest zeros. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 23 2011

a(n) = M^n*{1,1,1,0,0,0,...], top entry term; where M is an infinite bidiagonal matrix with all 1's in the superdiagonal, (1,2,3,...) as the main diagonal, and the rest zeros. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 24 2011

A007052.name: Number of order-consecutive partitions of n.
formula: Second binomial transform of (1, 1, 2, 2, 4, 4, ...). a(n) = Sum_{k=1..floor(n/2)}, C(n, 2k)*2^(n-k-1). - _Paul Barry_, Nov 22 2003

a(n) = both left and right terms in M^n * [1 1 1], where M = the 3 X 3 matrix [1 1 1 / 1 2 1 / 1 1 1]. M^n * [1 1 1] = [a(n) A007070(n) a(n)]. E.g., a(3) = 34. M^3 * [1 1 1] = [34 48 34] (center term is A007070(3)). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 18 2004
The i-th term of the sequence is the entry (2, 2) in the i-th power of the 2 X 2 matrix M = ((1, 1), (1, 3)). - _Simone Severini_, Oct 15 2005

If p[i]=Fibonacci(2i-1) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)= det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010
G.f.: G(0)*(1-x)/(2*x) + 1 - 1/x, where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k-1)/(x*(2*k+1) - (1-x)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013
a(n) = a(-2-n) * 2^(n+1) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 25 2017

A007054.name: Super ballot numbers: 6(2n)!/(n!(n+2)!).
formula: G.f.: c(x)*(4-c(x)), where c(x) = g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108; Convolution of Catalan numbers with negative Catalan numbers but -C(0)=-1 replaced by 3. - _Wolfdieter Lang_

E.g.f. in Maple notation: exp(2*x)*(4*x*(BesselI(0, 2*x)-BesselI(1, 2*x))-BesselI(1, 2*x))/x. Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on [0, 4], in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*(4-x)^(3/2)/x^(1/2), x=0..4)/(2*Pi), n=0, 1... This representation is unique. - _Karol A. Penson_, Oct 10 2001
D-finite with recurrence (n+2)*a(n) +2*(-2*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 03 2012
G.f.: 1/(x^2*G(0)) + 3/x -1/2/x^2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x*(2*k+3)/(2*x*(2*k+3) + (k+1)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 06 2013
G.f.: 3/x - 1/(2*x^2) + G(0)/(4*x^2), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - 2*x*(2*k-3)/(2*x*(2*k-3) + (k+1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 18 2013
0 = a(n)*(+16*a(n+1) - 14*a(n+2)) + a(n+1)*(+6*a(n+1) + a(n+2)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 18 2014
A002421(n+2) = 2*a(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 18 2014

A007055.name: Let S denote the palindromes in the language {0,1}*; a(n) = number of words of length n in the language SS.
formula: a(n) = A187272(n) - Sum_{d|n, d<n} phi(n/d)*a(d). - _Andrew Howroyd_, Mar 29 2016

A007056.name: Let S denote the palindromes in the language {0,1,2}*; a(n) = number of words of length n in the language SS.
formula: a(n) = A187273(n) - Sum_{d|n,d<n} phi(n/d)*a(d). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Sep 27 2017

A007057.name: Let S denote the palindromes in the language {0,1,2,3}*; a(n) = number of words of length n in the language SS.
formula: a(n) = A187274(n) - Sum_{d|n,d<n} phi(n/d)*a(d). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Sep 27 2017

A007058.name: Let S denote the palindromes in the language {0,1,2,3,4}*; a(n) = number of words of length n in the language SS.
formula: a(n) = A187275(n) - Sum_{d|n,d<n} phi(n/d)*a(d). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Sep 27 2017

A007059.name: Number of balanced ordered trees with n nodes.
formula: Define generalized Fibonacci numbers by Sum_{h>=0} F(p, h)z^n = z^(p-1)(1-z)/(1-2z+z^p+1). Then a(n) = 1+Sum{2<=h<=n} F(h-1, n-2).

A007060.name: Number of ways n couples can sit in a row without any spouses next to each other.
formula: a(n) = n!*hypergeom([ -n, n+1],[],1/2)*(-2)^n. - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 13 2009
For n >= 1, int_{x = 0..1} (x^2 - 1)^n*exp(x) dx = a(n)*e - A177840(n). Hence A177840(n)/a(n) -> e as n -> infinity (End)
a(n) ~ sqrt(Pi) * 2^(2*n+1) * n^(2*n + 1/2) / exp(2*n+1). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 09 2016

A007061.name: The Ehrenfeucht-Mycielski sequence (1,2-version): a maximally unpredictable sequence.

A007062.name: Let P(n) of a sequence s(1),s(2),s(3),... be obtained by leaving s(1),...,s(n) fixed and reversing every n consecutive terms thereafter; apply P(2) to 1,2,3,... to get PS(2), then apply P(3) to PS(2) to get PS(3), then apply P(4) to PS(3), etc. The limit of PS(n) is A007062.

A007063.name: Main diagonal of Kimberling's expulsion array (A035486).
formula: a(theta(k)) = 3*theta(k)-(k+1), where theta(k) = Sum_{i=0..k-1} 2^floor(i/3). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Feb 23 2010

A007064.name: Numbers not of form "nearest integer to n*tau", tau=(1+sqrt(5))/2.

A007065.name: Number of M-sequences from multicomplexes on at most 5 variables with no monomial of degree greater than n.

A007066.name: a(n) = 1 + ceiling((n-1)*phi^2), phi = (1+sqrt(5))/2.
formula: a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n)=a(n-1)+2 if n is already in the sequence, a(n)=a(n-1)+3 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 06 2003

A007067.name: Nearest integer to n*tau.
formula: Satisfies a(a(n)) = a(n) + n. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 14 2006

A007068.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + (3+(-1)^n)*a(n-2)/2.
formula: a(2n+1)=a(2n)+a(2n-1); a(2n)=a(2n-1)+2*a(2n-2); same recurrence (mod parity) as A001882) - _Len Smiley_, Feb 05 2001.
a(n)=sum{k=0..n, sum{j=0..n, C(floor(n/2), n-j)*C(floor(j/2), j-k)}} - _Paul Barry_, Feb 14 2005
a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) * A000034(n-1). [_Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jan 21 2012]

A007069.name: First column of spectral array W(sqrt 2).

A007070.name: a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 2*a(n-2) with a(0) = 1, a(1) = 4.
formula: Preceded by 0, this is the binomial transform of the Pell numbers A000129. Its e.g.f. is then exp(2x)*sinh(sqrt(2)x)/sqrt(2). - _Paul Barry_, May 09 2003
a(n) = ((2+sqrt(2))^(n+1) - (2-sqrt(2))^(n+1))/sqrt(8). - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), Dec 27 2008, corrected Mar 28 2011
This is the binomial mean transform of A002307. See Spivey and Steil (2006). - Michael Z. Spivey (mspivey(AT)ups.edu), Feb 26 2006
a(2n) = Sum_{r=0..n} 2^(2n-1-r)*(4*binomial(2n-1,2r) + 3*binomial(2n-1,2r+1)) a(2n-1) = Sum_{r=0..n} 2^(2n-2-r)*(4*binomial(2n-2,2r) + 3*binomial(2n-2,2r+1)). - _Jeffrey Liese_, Oct 12 2006
G.f.: 1/(1 - 4*x + 2*x^2) = 1/( x*(1 + U(0)) ) - 1/x  where U(k)= 1 - 2^k/(1 - x/(x - 2^k/U(k+1) )); (continued fraction 3rd kind, 3-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 05 2012
G.f.: A(x) = G(0)/(1-2*x) where G(k) = 1 + 2*x/(1 - 2*x - x*(1-2*x)/(x + (1-2*x)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 04 2013
G.f.: G(0)/(2*x) - 1/x, where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k-1)/(x*(2*k+1) - (1-x)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013

A007071.name: First row of 2-shuffle of spectral array W( sqrt 2 ).

A007072.name: First column of array associated with monotonic justified array.

A007073.name: First column of array associated with lexicographically justified array.

A007074.name: First column of array associated with reverse lexicographically justified array.

A007075.name: Number of irreducible positions of size n in Montreal solitaire.
formula: a(n) = d(n, 1) where d(n, k) is defined in A007046. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 06 2017

The ordinary generating function is f(1), where f(v) satisfies the functional equation f(v) = v*(1 + f(1 + x*v) - f(1)). The variable x marks inversions and v marks left-to-right minima. - _David Bevan_, Dec 19 2017

A007076.name: Number of irreducible positions of size n in Montreal solitaire.
formula: a(n) = d(n, 3) where d(n, k) is defined in A007046. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 06 2017

A007077.name: Optimal cost of search tree for searching an ordered array of n elements with cost k of probing element k.
formula: a(n) = m(n, 0) where m(0, d) = 0 and for n > 0, m(n, d) = min_{1 <= r <= n} {(r+d) * n + m(r-1, d) + m(n-r, r+d)} [from Knight]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 07 2017

A007079.name: Number of labeled regular tournaments with 2n+1 nodes.
formula: a(n) is the coefficient of (x1 x2 ... xn)^((n-1)/2) in (x1+x2)(x1+x3)...(x(n-1)+xn). - Jim Ferry (ferry(AT)metsci.com), Sep 29 2005

A007080.name: Number of labeled Eulerian digraphs with n nodes.

A007081.name: Number of labeled Eulerian oriented graphs with n nodes.
formula: a(n) = coefficient of [x_1*x_2*...*x_n]^(n-1) in Product_{1<=i<j<=n} (x_i^2 + x_j^2 + x_i*x_j). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 08 2017

A007082.name: Number of Eulerian circuits on the complete graph K_{2n+1}, divided by (n-1)!^{2n+1}.

A007084.name: Number of unlabeled trivalent 3-connected bipartite planar graphs with 2n nodes without subgraphs R2 and R4.

A007085.name: Number of unlabeled trivalent 3-connected bipartite planar graphs with 2n nodes without subgraphs R1 and R4.

A007087.name: Next term is uniquely the sum of 3 earlier terms.

A007088.name: The binary numbers (or binary words, or binary vectors, or binary expansion of n): numbers written in base 2.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..m} d(i)*10^i, where Sum_{i=0..m} d(i)*2^i is the base 2 representation of n.
G.f.: 1/(1-x) * Sum_{k>=0} 10^k * x^(2^k)/(1+x^(2^k)) - for sequence as decimal integers. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Jun 16 2006
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(log_2(n))} floor((Mod(n/2^k, 2)))*(10^k). - _José de Jesús Camacho Medina_, Jul 24 2014

A007089.name: Numbers in base 3.
formula: a(0)=0, a(n) = 10*a(n/3) if n==0 (mod 3), a(n) = a(n-1) + 1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002

A007090.name: Numbers in base 4.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d(i)*10^i: i=0, 1, ..., m}, where Sum_{d(i)*4^i: i=0, 1, ..., m} is the base 4 representation of n.
a(0) = 0, a(n) = 10*a(n/4) if n==0 (mod 4), a(n) = a(n-1)+1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002

A007091.name: Numbers in base 5.
formula: a(0)=0 a(n)=10*a(n/5) if n==0 (mod 5) a(n)=a(n-1)+1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002

A007092.name: Numbers in base 6.
formula: a(0)=0, a(n) = 10*a(n/6) if n==0 (mod 6), and a(n) = a(n-1)+1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002
a(n) = Sum{d(i)*10^i: i=0,1,...,m}, where Sum{d(i)*6^i: i=1,2,...,m} = n, and d(i) in {0,1,...,5}. - _Karol Bacik_, Sep 25 2012

A007093.name: Numbers in base 7.
formula: a(0) = 0, a(n) = 10*a(n/7) if n==0 (mod 7), a(n) = a(n-1)+1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002

A007094.name: Numbers in base 8.
formula: a(0) = 0; a(n) = 10*a(n/8) if n == 0 (mod 8); a(n) = a(n-1) + 1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002

A007095.name: Numbers in base 9.
formula: a(0) = 0, a(n) = 10*a(n/9) if n==0 (mod 9), a(n) = a(n-1)+1 otherwise. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 22 2002
Sum_{n>1} 1/a(n) = A082838 = 22.92067... (Kempner series). - _Bernard Schott_, Dec 29 2018; edited by _M. F. Hasler_, Jan 13 2020

A007096.name: Expansion of theta_3 / theta_4.
formula: Euler transform of period 4 sequence [4, -2, 4, 0, ...]. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 22 2005
Expansion of eta(q^2)^6 /(eta(q)^4 * eta(q^4)^2) in powers of q.

Expansion of phi(q) / phi(-q) = chi(q)^2 / chi(-q)^2 = psi(q)^2 / psi(-q)^2 = phi(-q^2)^2 / phi(-q)^2 = phi(q)^2 / phi(-q^2)^2 = chi(-q^2)^2 / chi(-q)^4 = chi(q)^4 / chi(-q^2)^2 = f(q)^2 / f(-q)^2 in powers of q where phi(), psi(), chi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^3)) where f(u, v) = (1 - u^4) * (1 - v^4) - (1 - u*v)^4. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 01 2006
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (16 t)) = (1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is g.f. for A028939.
Expansion of Jacobian elliptic function 1 / sqrt(k') in powers of q. - see Fine.
G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2)) where f(u, v) = 1 + u^2 - 2*u*v^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 07 2005
Unique solution to f(x^2)^2 = (f(x) + 1 / f(x)) / 2 and f(0)=1, f'(0) nonzero.

A007097.name: Primeth recurrence: a(n+1) = a(n)-th prime.
formula: a(n) = prime^{[n]}(1), with the prime function prime(k) = A000040(k), with a(0) = 1. See the name and the programs. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 03 2018

A007098.name: Number of unlabeled bisectable trees with 2n+1 nodes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(k + 1, 2) * A228601(n, k). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Oct 10 2017

A007100.name: Number of labeled trivalent (or cubic) 3-connected graphs with 2n nodes.

Let P(n+1) = the number of integer partitions of (n+1); let p(i) = the number of parts of the i-th partition of (n+1); let d(i) = the number of different parts of the i-th partition of (n+1); let m(i, j) = multiplicity of the j-th part of the i-th partition of (n+1). Define the operator Sum_{i=1..P(n+1), p(i)=k+1} as the sum running from i=1 to i=P(n+1) but taking only partitions with p(i)=(k+1) parts into account. Define the operator Product_{j=1..d(i)} = product running from j=1 to j=d(i). Then C(n, k) = Sum_{p(i)=(k+1), i=1..P(n+1)} p(i)! / [Product_{j=1..d(i)} m(i, j)!]. E.g., C(5, 3) = 10 because n=6 has the following partitions with m=3 parts: (114), (123), (222). For their multiplicities one has: (114): 3!/(2!*1!) = 3; (123): 3!/(1!*1!*1!) = 6; (222): 3!/3! = 1. The sum is 3 + 6 + 1 = 10 = C(5, 3). - _Thomas Wieder_, Jun 03 2005
C(n, k) = Sum_{j=0..k} = (-1)^j*C(n+1+j, k-j)*A000108(j). - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 10 2005

C(t+p-1, t) = Sum_{i=0..t} C(i+p-2, i) = Sum_{i=1..p} C(i+t-2, t-1). A binomial number is the sum of its left parent and all its right ancestors, which equals the sum of its right parent and all its left ancestors. - Lee Naish (lee(AT)cs.mu.oz.au), Mar 07 2008

Recurrence equation: T(n,k) = T(n-1,k)*(n + k)/(n - k) - T(n-1,k-1) for n >= 2 and 1 <= k < n, with boundary conditions T(n,0) = T(n,n) = 1. Note, changing the minus sign in the recurrence to a plus sign gives a recurrence for the square of the binomial coefficients - see A008459.

There is a relation between the e.g.f.'s of the rows and the diagonals of the triangle, namely, exp(x) * e.g.f. for row n = e.g.f. for diagonal n. For example, for n = 3 we have exp(x)*(1 + 3*x + 3*x^2/2! + x^3/3!) = 1 + 4*x + 10*x^2/2! + 20*x^3/3! + 35*x^4/4! + .... This property holds more generally for the Riordan arrays of the form ( f(x), x/(1 - x) ), where f(x) is an o.g.f. of the form 1 + f_1*x + f_2*x^2 + .... See, for example, A055248 and A106516.
Let P denote the present triangle. For k = 0,1,2,... define P(k) to be the lower unit triangular block array

\ 0  P/ having the k X k identity matrix I_k as the upper left block; in particular, P(0) = P. The infinite product P(0)*P(1)*P(2)*..., which is clearly well-defined, is equal to the triangle of Stirling numbers of the second kind A008277. The row polynomials of the Pascal matrix P(n,x) = (1+x)^n are related to the Bernoulli polynomials Br(n,x) and their umbral compositional inverses Bv(n,x) by the umbral relation P(n,x) = (-Br(.,-Bv(.,x)))^n = (-1)^n Br(n,-Bv(.,x)), which translates into the matrix relation P = M * Br * M * Bv, where P is the Pascal matrix, M is the diagonal matrix diag(1,-1,1,-1,...), Br is the matrix for the coefficients of the Bernoulli polynomials, and Bv that for the umbral inverse polynomials defined umbrally by Br(n,Bv(.,x)) = x^n = Bv(n,Br(.,x)). A007416.name: The minimal numbers: sequence A005179 arranged in increasing order.

A007417.name: If k appears, 3k does not.
formula: Partial sums of A092400. Indices of even numbers in A007949. Indices of odd numbers in A051064. a(n) = A092401(2n-1). - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 29 2004
{a(n)} = A052330({A042948(n)}), where {a(n)} denotes the set of integers in the sequence. - _Peter Munn_, Aug 31 2019

A007418.name: Numerators of expansion of exp x / sin x.

A007419.name: Largest number not the sum of distinct n-th-order polygonal numbers.

A007421.name: Liouville's function: parity of number of primes dividing n (with multiplicity).
formula: a(n) = ((-1)^bigomega(n)+3)/2, where bigomega(n) is the number of prime divisors of the integer n counted with multiplicity.

A007422.name: Multiplicatively perfect numbers n: product of divisors of n is n^2.

A007423.name: mu(n) + 1, where mu is the Moebius function.

A007424.name: a(n) = 1 if n is squarefree, otherwise 2.

A007425.name: d_3(n), or tau_3(n), the number of ordered factorizations of n as n = r s t.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d dividing n} tau(d). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 04 2002
For n = Product p_i^e_i, a(n) = Product_i A000217(e_i + 1). - _Lekraj Beedassy_, Sep 07 2004
a(n^2) = tau_3(n^2) = tau_2(n^2)*tau_2(n), where tau_2 is A000005 and tau_3 is this sequence.
a(s) = 3^omega(s), if s>1 is a squarefree number (A005117) and omega(s) is: A001221. (End)
a(n) = tau_3(n) = tau_2(n)*tau_2(n*rad(n))/tau_2(rad(n)), where rad(n) is A007947 and tau_2(n) is A000005.
The first formula follows from the first Cloitre formula and a Liouville formula; the second formula follows from our analogous formula (cf. our comment in Formula section of A000005). (End)
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(tau(k)/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 23 2018

A007426.name: d_4(n), or tau_4(n), the number of ordered factorizations of n as n = rstu.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d dividing n} tau(d)*tau(n/d). - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 12 2003
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} tau_3(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 30 2018

A007427.name: Moebius transform applied twice to sequence 1,0,0,0,....
formula: Multiplicative function with a(p^e) = binomial(2, e)*(-1)^e for p prime and e >= 0.
a(n^2) = A008683(n)^2. a(A005117(n)) = (-2)^A001221(A005117(n)). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jun 27 2011 [Misrendering of contribution rectified by _Peter Munn_, Mar 06 2020]
a(n) is the Dirichlet inverse of A000005, which means a(n) = -Sum_{d|n, d<n} A000005(n/d)*a(d). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 19 2013
a(n) = 0 if n is not cubefree: A046099, otherwise sign(a(n))= lambda(n), where lambda is A008836. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 19 2013
Dirichlet g.f. of |a(n)|: zeta(s)^2/zeta(2s)^2 (conjectured). - _Ralf Stephan_, Jul 05 2013
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x - Sum_{k>=2} tau(k)*A(x^k), where tau = A000005. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 11 2019

A007428.name: Moebius transform applied thrice to sequence 1,0,0,0,....
formula: a(s) = (-3)^A001221(s) provided s is a squarefree number (A005117). (End)

A007429.name: Inverse Moebius transform applied twice to natural numbers.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} sigma(d), Dirichlet convolution of A000203 and A000012. - _Jason Earls_, Jul 07 2001
Moebius transform of A007430. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 03 2004
Equals A051731^2 * [1, 2, 3, ...]. Equals row sums of triangle A134577. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 02 2007
Row sums of triangle A134699. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 06 2007
a(n) = n * (Sum_{d|n} tau(d)/d) = n * (A276736(n) / A276737(n)). - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Sep 24 2016
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(sigma(k)/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 26 2018

A007430.name: Inverse Moebius transform applied thrice to natural numbers.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = Sum_{k=0..e} binomial(e-k+2, e-k)*p^k.
Row sums of triangle A134676. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 05 2007
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Pi^6 * n^2 / 432. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 06 2018

A007431.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} phi(d)*mu(n/d).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p) = p-2 and a(p^e) = p^e - 2*p^(e-1) + p^(e-2) for e > 1. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 25 2002
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} mu(gcd(n,k)) for n > 0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jun 14 2007
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} (phi(gcd(k,n)) * cos(2*Pi*k/n)). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 18 2013
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} tau_{-2}(d)*n/d = Sum_{d|n} tau_{-3}(d)*sigma_1(n/d), where tau_{-3} is A007428, tau_{-2} A007427 and sigma_1 A000203. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 19 2013
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = Sum_{n>=1} mu(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n)^2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 25 2017
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 18 * n^2 / Pi^4. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 04 2018
Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = Sum_{n>=1} phi(n)*x^n. - _Mamuka Jibladze_, Aug 09 2019

A007432.name: Moebius transform applied thrice to natural numbers.
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = sum (-1)^k (3 choose k)p^(e-k)[e>=k], k=0..3
a(n)=Sum{d|n} tau_{-3}(d)*n/d = Sum{d|n} tau_{-2}(d)*phi(n/d), where tau_{-3} is A007428 and tau_{-2} A007427. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 19 2013
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 108 * n^2 / Pi^6. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 04 2018

A007433.name: Inverse Moebius transform applied twice to squares.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} sigma_2(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k), where sigma_2(k) is the sum of squares of divisors of k (A001157). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 16 2017
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta(s-2)*zeta(s)^2. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Jul 14 2018
a(n) is multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(2*e + 4) - (e+2) * p^2 + e+1)) / (p^2 - 1)^2. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 15 2018
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Zeta(3)^2 * n^3 / 3. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 04 2018

A007434.name: Jordan function J_2(n) (a generalization of phi(n)).
formula: Multiplicative with a(p^e) = p^(2e) - p^(2e-2). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 26 2001
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} d^2 * mu(n/d). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 05 2002
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} phi(d)*phi(n/d)*n/d; Sum_{d|n} a(d) = n^2. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 20 2005
Dirichlet generating function: zeta(s-2)/zeta(s). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Sep 11 2005
Dirichlet inverse of A046970. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 11 2014
If n > 1, then 1 > a(n)/n^2 > 1/zeta(2). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jul 14 2011
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} phi(n^2/d)*mu(d)^2). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jul 24 2012
a(n) = Sum_{k = 1..n} gcd(k, n)^2 * cos(2*Pi*k/n). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Jan 18 2013
a(1) + a(2) + ... + a(n) ~ 1/(3*zeta(3))*n^3 + O(n^2). Lambert series Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = x*(1 + x)/(1 - x)^3. - _Peter Bala_, Dec 23 2013
a(n) = 24 * A115000(n) unless n < 5. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 12 2008
a(n) = A001065(n) - A134675(n). - Conjectured by _John Mason_ and proved by _Max Alekseyev_, Jan 07 2015
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} gcd(n, k) * phi(gcd(n, k)), where phi(k) is the Euler totient function. - _Daniel Suteu_, Jun 15 2018
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)*x^k*(1 + x^k)/(1 - x^k)^3. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 24 2018

A007435.name: Inverse Moebius transform of Fibonacci numbers 1,1,2,3,5,8,...
formula: Row sums of A051731 * A127647. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 22 2007
G.f.: Sum_{k>0} Fibonacci(k)*x^k/(1-x^k) = Sum_{k>0} x^k/(1-x^k-x^(2*k)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 17 2002
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(Fibonacci(k)/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 20 2018
a(n) ~ 5^(-1/2) * phi^n, where phi = A001622 = (1 + sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 21 2018

A007436.name: Moebius transform of Fibonacci numbers.
formula: Row sums of the triangle generated by A054525 * A127647. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 22 2007
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = x/(1 - x - x^2). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 25 2017

A007437.name: Inverse Moebius transform of triangular numbers.
formula: Coefficients in expansion of Sum_{n >= 1} x^n/(1-x^n)^3.
Row sums of triangles A134544 and A134545. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 31 2007
Row sums of triangle A134839 - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 12 2007
Dirichlet g.f. zeta(s)*(zeta(s-1)+zeta(s-2))/2. [From _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Nov 05 2009]
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^((k+1)/2)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 12 2018
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Zeta(3) * n^3 / 6. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 06 2018

A007438.name: Moebius transform of triangular numbers.
formula: a(n) = (A007434(n)+A000010(n))/2, half the sum of the Mobius transforms of n^2 and n. Dirichlet g.f. (zeta(s-2)+zeta(s-1))/(2*zeta(s)). - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 09 2011
G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = x/(1 - x)^3. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 25 2017

A007439.name: Number of planted trees: all sub-rooted trees from any node are identical; non-root, non-leaf nodes an even distance from the root are of degree 2.
formula: a(n+2) = Sum a(k), k|n. Shifts left two places under inverse Moebius transformation.
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x + x^2 * (1 + A(x) + A(x^2) + A(x^3) + ...). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 09 2019

A007440.name: Reversion of g.f. for Fibonacci numbers 1,1,2,3,5,...
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n, 2k)*C(k)*(-1)^(n-k), where C(n) is A000108(n). - _Paul Barry_, May 16 2005
a(n) = 2^(-n-1)*Sum_{k=floor((n-1)/2)..n} binomial(k+1,n-k)*5^(n-k)*(-1)^k*C(k), n > 0, where C(k) is A000108. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Sep 21 2010
G.f.: (G(0)-x-1)/(x^2) = 1/G(0) where G(k) = 1 + x + x^2/G(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 25 2011
-1/A(-x) = 1/x - 1 + x + x^2 - 2*x^4 - 3*x^5 + x^6 + 11*x^7 + 15*x^8 - 13*x^9 + ... is the Laurent series generating function for A214649. (End)
G.f.: A(x) = x*B(-x), where B(x) is the g.f. of A343773.

A007441.name: 1 + Sum_{n=1..inf} a_n x^n = Product_{n=1..inf} (1-x^n)^prime(n).
formula: a(n) = 1/n*Sum_{k=1..n} a(n-k)*b(k), k>0, a(0)=1, b(k)=-Sum_{d|k} d*ithprime(k), cf. A061150.

A007442.name: Inverse binomial transform of primes.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} prime(k)*x^k/(1 + x)^k. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 23 2019

A007443.name: Binomial transform of primes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(n-1,k-1)*prime(k). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 02 2017
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} prime(k)*x^k/(1 - x)^k. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 21 2019

A007444.name: Moebius transform of primes.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/(1 - x^n) = Sum_{n>=1} prime(n)*x^n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 25 2017
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} prime(d)*mu(n/d), where mu is the Moebius function (A008683). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 23 2020

A007445.name: Inverse Moebius transform of primes.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} prime(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 02 2017

A007447.name: Logarithm of e.g.f. for primes.
formula: E.g.f.: log(1 + Sum_{k>=1} prime(k)*x^k/k!). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 10 2018

A007448.name: Knuth's sequence (or Knuth numbers): a(n+1) = 1 + min( 2*a(floor(n/2)), 3*a(floor(n/3)) ).

A007449.name: a(0) = 7, a(1) = 9; for n >= 0, a(2n+1) = a(2n-1)^2 - a(2n-2), a(2n+2) = a(2n)^2 - a(2n+1).
formula: a(n+1) = a(n-1)^2 - a(n - 2*(1 - n mod 2)), a(0)=7, a(1)=9. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 25 2003

A007451.name: Denominators of expansion of exp x / sin x.

A007452.name: Expand cos x / exp x and invert nonzero coefficients.

A007453.name: Number of unlabeled connected series-parallel posets with n nodes.
formula: See the 1989 and 1997 papers by Cameron cited above for generating functions, and the 1997 paper for asymptotics.
Inverse Euler transform of A003430. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 04 2018
a(n) = A003430(n) - A007454(n) for n > 1. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 04 2018

A007454.name: Number of unlabeled disconnected series-parallel posets with n nodes.
formula: a(n) = A003430(n) - A007453(n) for n > 1. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 04 2018

A007455.name: Number of subsequences of [ 1,...,n ] in which each odd number has an even neighbor.
formula: G.f. = (1 + x + 2 x^3)/(1 - 3 x^2 - 2 x^4). - _Harvey P. Dale_, Feb 18 2011, edited by _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 19 2019

A007456.name: Days required to spread gossip to n people.

A007458.name: Order of group of n X n X n Rubik cube.

A007459.name: Higgs's primes: a(n+1) = smallest prime > a(n) such that a(n+1)-1 divides the product (a(1)...a(n))^2.

A007460.name: Shifts left under OR-convolution with itself.

A007461.name: Shifts left under AND-convolution with itself.

A007462.name: Shifts left under XOR-convolution with itself.

A007463.name: Shifts left under lcm-convolution with itself.

A007464.name: Shifts left under GCD-convolution with itself.

A007465.name: Exponential-convolution of triangular numbers with themselves.

A007466.name: Exponential-convolution of natural numbers with themselves.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..(n+2)} C(n+2, k) * floor(k/2)^2. - _Paul Barry_, Mar 06 2003
E.g.f.: U(0) where U(k)= 1 + 2*x/( 1 - x/(2 + x - 4/( 2 + x*(k+1)/U(k+1)))) ; (continued fraction, 3rd kind, 4-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 28 2012

A007468.name: Sum of next n primes.
formula: a(n) = prime(1 + n(n-1)/2) + ... + prime(n + n(n-1)/2), where prime(i) is i-th prime.

A007469.name: Shifts left 2 places under Stirling2 transform.

A007470.name: Shifts left when Stirling2 transform is applied twice.

A007471.name: Sum of digits of n a(n) is n ( = A003634/n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A007472.name: Shifts 2 places left when binomial transform applied twice.

A007473.name: Dimension of space of Vassiliev knot invariants of order n.
formula: Broadhurst gives a conjectured explicit g.f. (different from A014595).

A007474.name: Number of circular chord diagrams with n chords, up to rotational symmetry.

A007475.name: a(n) is the smallest positive number such that the sum of A001032(n) consecutive squares starting with a(n)^2 is a square.

A007476.name: Shifts 2 places left under binomial transform.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies A(x) = 1 + x + (x^2/(1-x))*A(x/(1-x)). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 28 2011

A007477.name: Shifts 2 places left when convolved with itself.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies the equation 0 = 1 + x - A(x) + (x*A(x))^2.
The g.f. satisfies A(x)-x^2*A(x)^2 = 1+x. - _Ralf Stephan_, Jun 30 2003
G.f.: (1+x)c(x^2(1+x)) where c(x) is g.f. of A000108. - _Paul Barry_, May 31 2006
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-2} binomial(2*k+2,n-k-2)*binomial(n-k-2,k)/(k+1), n>1, a(0)=1, a(1)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 22 2014
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} (-1)^(n-1-k)*binomial(n-1,k)*A082582(k+2), for n>0. - _Thomas Baruchel_, Jan 22 2015

A007478.name: Dimension of primitive Vassiliev knot invariants of order n.
formula: Lim [n -> infinity] a(n) = n log n [Chmutov and Duzhin] - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Jul 24 2008

A007480.name: a(n) = denominator of sum_{k=1..n} k^(-4).
formula: a(n) = denominator of (Pi^4/90 - zeta(4, n+1)). - _Arkadiusz Wesolowski_, Nov 23 2012
Denominators of coefficients in expansion of PolyLog(4, x)/(1 - x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 10 2017

A007481.name: Number of subsequences of [ 1,...,n ] in which each even number has an odd neighbor.

A007482.name: a(n) is the number of subsequences of [ 1, ..., 2n ] in which each odd number has an even neighbor.
formula: Let b(0) = 1, b(k) = floor(b(k-1)) + 2/b(k-1); then, for n>0, b(n) = a(n)/a(n-1). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 09 2002
The Hankel transform of this sequence is [1,2,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,...]. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 21 2007
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} binomial(n-k, k)2^k*3^(n-2k). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 23 2005
a(n) = - a(-2-n) * (-2)^(n+1) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 03 2015
If c = (3 + sqrt(17))/2, then c^n = (A206776(n) + sqrt(17)*a(n-1)) / 2. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 13 2016
a(n) = round(((sqrt(17) + 3)/2)^(n+1)/sqrt(17)). The distance of the argument from the nearest integer is about 1/2^(n+3). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 16 2019

A007483.name: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2), with a(0)=1, a(1)=5.
formula: a(n) = upper left term in the 2 X 2 matrix [1,2; 2,2]^(n+1). Also [a(n), a(n+1)] = the 2 X 2 matrix [0,1; 2,3]^(n+1) * [1,1]. Example: [0,1; 2,3]^4 * [1,1] = [61, 217]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 16 2008
This sequence seems to be generated by the floretion - 0.5'i + 0.5j' + 0.25'ii' + 0.25'jj' - 0.75'kk' + 'ij' - 'ji' - 0.5'jk' - 0.5'ki' - 0.75e ("emseq"). - _Creighton Dement_, Nov 25 2004

A007484.name: a(n) = 3*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2), with a(0)=2, a(1)=7.
formula: a(n) = nearest integer to (and converges rapidly to) (1+4/sqrt(17))*((3+sqrt(17))/2)^n. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jul 30 2016

If p[i] = Fibonacci(i+2) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)= det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010

A007485.name: Number of letters in n (in Dutch).

A007487.name: Sum of 9th powers.
formula: a(n) = n^2*(n+1)^2*(n^2+n-1)*(2*n^4+4*n^3-n^2-3*n+3)/20 (see MathWorld, Power Sum, formula 39). a(n) = n*A000542(n) - Sum_{i=0..n-1} A000542(i). - _Bruno Berselli_, Apr 26 2010
a(n) = -Sum_{j=1..9} j*s(n+1,n+1-j)*S(n+9-j,n), where s(n,k) and S(n,k) are the Stirling numbers of the first kind and the second kind, respectively. - _Mircea Merca_, Jan 25 2014

A007488.name: Primes whose reversal is a square.

A007489.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k!.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} P(n, k)/C(n, k). - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 21 2004
Starting (1, 3, 9, 33, 153, ...), = row sums of triangle A137593 - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 28 2008
a(n) = a(n-1) + n! for n >= 1. - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Jun 16 2009
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies to the differential equation A'(x)=A(x)+x/(1-x)^2+1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jan 22 2011
a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(n) = (n+1)*a(n-1)-n*a(n-2). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 05 2012
G.f.: W(0)*x/(2-2*x) , where W(k) = 1 + 1/( 1 - x*(k+2)/( x*(k+2) + 1/W(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 19 2013
G.f.: x /(1-x)/Q(0),m=+2, where Q(k) = 1 - 2*x*(2*k+1) - m*x^2*(k+1)*(2*k+1)/( 1 - 2*x*(2*k+2) - m*x^2*(k+1)*(2*k+3)/Q(k+1) ) ; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 24 2013
E.g.f.: exp(x-1)*(Ei(1) - Ei(1-x)) - exp(x) + 1/(1 - x), where Ei(x) is the exponential integral. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Nov 27 2016

A007490.name: Primes of form x^3 + y^3 + z^3 where x,y,z > 0.

A007493.name: Decimal expansion of Wallis' number, the real root of x^3 - 2*x - 5.

A007494.name: Numbers that are congruent to 0 or 2 mod 3.
formula: If u(1)=0, u(n) = n + floor(u(n-1)/3), then a(n-1) = u(n). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Nov 26 2002
a(n) = 3*floor(n/2) + 2*(n mod 2) = A032766(n) + A000035(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 04 2005
a(n) = 2n - floor(n/2) = floor((3n+1)/2) = n + (n + (n mod 2))/2. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 19 2013
a(n) = n + floor(n/2) + (n mod 2). - _Bruno Berselli_, Apr 04 2016
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} numerator(2/i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Feb 26 2017
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} Sum_{i=0..k} C(i,k)+(-1)^(k-i). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Sep 20 2017

A007495.name: Josephus problem: survivors.
formula: Let t(k,n) = (t(k-1,n) + n) mod k and t(1,n) = 0; then a(n) = t(n,n) + 1. - _Gerhard Kirchner_, Oct 23 2016

A007496.name: Numbers n such that the decimal expansions of 2^n and 5^n contain no 0's (probably 33 is last term).

A007497.name: a(1) = 2, a(n) = sigma(a(n-1)).
formula: Conjecture: a(n) == 0 mod 9 for n > 34. - _Ivan N. Ianakiev_, Mar 27 2014

Checked up to n = 1000. Similar statements hold for other small primes. For example, a(n) seems to be divisible by 2^22 * 3^5 * 5 * 7 = 35672555520 for all n > 99. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 27 2014

A007498.name: Unique period lengths of primes mentioned in A007615.

A007500.name: Primes whose reversal in base 10 is also prime (called "palindromic primes" by D. Wells, although that name usually refers to A002385). Also called reversible primes.

A007502.name: Les Marvin sequence: a(n) = F(n)+(n-1)*F(n-1), F() = Fibonacci numbers.

A007503.name: Number of subgroups of dihedral group: sigma(n) + d(n).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} tau(p^d), where tau is A000005 and p any prime. - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Apr 14 2012
a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} d+1. - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 14 2013
L.g.f.: -log(Product_{k>=1} (1 - x^k)^(1+1/k)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)*x^n/n. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 23 2018

A007504.name: Sum of the first n primes.
formula: a(n) has the asymptotic expression a(n) ~ n^2 * log(n) / 2. - Ahmed Fares (ahmedfares(AT)my-deja.com), Apr 24 2001 (see Bach & Shallit 1996)
a(n) = min(A068873(n), A073619(n)) for n > 1. - _Jonathan Sondow_, Jul 10 2012

For n >= 3, a(n) >= (n-1)^2 * (log(n-1) - 1/2)/2 and a(n) <= n*(n+1)*(log(n) + log(log(n))+ 1)/2. Thus a(n) = n^2 * log(n) / 2 + O(n^2*log(log(n))). It is more precise than in Fares's comment. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Aug 01 2013
a(n) = (n^2/2)*(log n + log log n - 3/2 + (log log n - 3)/log n + (2 (log log n)^2 - 14 log log n + 27)/(4 log^2 n) + O((log log n/log n)^3)) [Sinha]. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jun 11 2015
G.f: (x*b(x))/(1-x), where b(x) is the g.f. of A000040. - _Mario C. Enriquez_, Dec 10 2016
a(n) = A008472(A002110(n)), for n>0. - _Michel Marcus_, Jul 16 2020

A007506.name: Primes p with property that p divides the sum of all primes <= p.

A007508.name: Number of twin prime pairs below 10^n.
formula: Partial sums of A070076(n). - _Lekraj Beedassy_, Jun 11 2004

For 1 < n < 19, a(n) ~ e * pi(10^n) / (5*n - 5) = e * A006880(n) / (5*n - 5) where e is Napier's constant, see A001113 (probably, so is for any n > 18; we use n > 1 to avoid division by zero). - _Sergey Pavlov_, Apr 07 2021

For any n, a(n) = qcc(x) - (10^n - pi(10^n) - pi(10^n + 2) + 1) where qcc(x) is the number of "common composite numbers" c <= 10^n such that c and c' = c + 2 both are composite (trivial). - _Sergey Pavlov_, Apr 08 2021

A007510.name: Single (or isolated or non-twin) primes: Primes p such that neither p-2 nor p+2 is prime.
formula: a(n) ~ n log n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 21 2017

A007511.name: a(n) is the smallest number greater than a(n-1) that is expressible as the sum of two squares in more ways than a(n-1).

A007512.name: Primes of the form floor(e*10^k), i.e., formed by concatenation of an initial segment of the decimal expansion of e.

A007513.name: a(n) = initial prime of n consecutive primes such that first and last have same digit sum.

A007514.name: Pi = Sum_{n >= 0} a(n)/n!.
formula: a(n) = floor(n!*Pi) - n*floor((n-1)!*Pi) for all n > 0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Mar 20 2017

A007518.name: a(n) = floor(n*(n+2)*(2*n-1)/8).
formula: a(n) = 3*A002623(n) for n>0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 15 2009

A007519.name: Primes of form 8n+1, that is, primes congruent to 1 mod 8.

A007522.name: Primes of the form 8n+7, that is, primes congruent to -1 mod 8.
formula: Equals A000040 INTERSECT A004215. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 22 2006

A007523.name: Primes in A092845 (decimal expansion of Pi written backwards).

A007525.name: Decimal expansion of log_2 e.
formula: More generally: 1/log(2) = Sum_{n = -infinity..infinity} (2^(n+x) / (1 + 2^2^(n+x))) for all real x. - _Nicolas Nagel_, Jul 02 2019

A007526.name: a(n) = n(a(n-1) + 1), a(0) = 0.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k!*C(n, k). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 06 2002
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} (n! / k!). - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 22 2004
Binomial transform of n! - !n. - _Paul Barry_, May 12 2004
Inverse binomial transform of A066534. - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 16 2004
For n > 0, a(n) = exp(1) * Integral_{x>=0} exp(-exp(x/n)+x) dx. - _Gerald McGarvey_, Oct 19 2006
E.g.f.: -1/G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 1/(x - x^3/(x^2+(k+1)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 10 2012
Conjecture : a(n) = (n+2)*a(n-1) - (2*n-1)*a(n-2) + (n-2)*a(n-3). - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 04 2012 [Conjecture verified by _Robert FERREOL_, Aug 04 2018]
G.f.: (Q(0) - 1)/(1-x), where Q(k)= 1 + (2*k + 1)*x/( 1 - x - 2*x*(1-x)*(k+1)/(2*x*(k+1) + (1-x)/Q(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 09 2013
G.f.: 2/((1-x)*G(0)) - 1/(1-x), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(2*k+2)/(x*(2*k+3) - 1 + x*(2*k+2)/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 31 2013
G.f.: Q(0)/(2-2*x) - 1/(1-x), where Q(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/(x*(k+1) + (1-x)/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 09 2013
G.f.: (W(0) - 1)/(1-x), where W(k) = 1 - x*(k+1)/( x*(k+2) - 1/(1 - x*(k+1)/( x*(k+1) - 1/W(k+1) ))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 25 2013
For n > 0: a(n) = n*A000522(n-1). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 27 2013
Product_{n>=1} (a(n)+1)/a(n) = e, coming from Product_{n=1..N}(a(n)+1)/a(n) = Sum_{n=0..N} 1/n!. - _Robert FERREOL_, Jul 12 2018

A007527.name: Numbers that are not the sum of 4 hexagonal numbers.

A007528.name: Primes of the form 6k-1.
formula: Legendre symbol (-3, a(n)) = -1 and (-3, A002476(n)) = +1, for n >= 1. For prime 3 one sets (-3, 3) = 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 03 2021

A007529.name: Prime triples: n; n+2 or n+4; n+6 all prime.

A007530.name: Prime quadruples: numbers k such that k, k+2, k+6, k+8 are all prime.

A007531.name: a(n) = n*(n-1)*(n-2) (or n!/(n-3)!).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} polygorial(3,i) where polygorial(3,i) = A028896(i-1). - Daniel Dockery (peritus(AT)gmail.com), Jun 16 2003
a(n+1) = n^3 - n. - _Mohammad K. Azarian_, Jul 26 2007
If the first 0 is eliminated, a(n) = floor(n^5/(n^2+1)). - _Gary Detlefs_, Feb 11 2010
Partial sums of A028896. - _R. J. Mathar_, Aug 28 2014
a(n)*a(n+1) + A000096(n-3)^2 = m^2 (a perfect square), m = ((a(n)+a(n+1))/2)-n. - _Ezhilarasu Velayutham_, May 21 2019

A007532.name: Handsome numbers: sum of positive powers of its digits; a(n) = Sum_{i=1..k} d[i]^e[i] where d[1..k] are the decimal digits of a(n), e[i] > 0.
formula: If n = d_1 d_2 ... d_k in decimal, then there are integers m_1, m_2, ..., m_k > 0 such that n = d_1^m_1 + ... + d_k^m_k.

A007534.name: Even numbers that are not the sum of a pair of twin primes.

A007535.name: Smallest pseudoprime ( > n ) to base n: smallest composite number m > n such that n^(m-1)-1 is divisible by m.

A007536.name: Numbers that are not the sum of 3 hexagonal numbers (probably finite).

A007537.name: Number of proper covers of an n-set.

A007538.name: A self-generating sequence: there are a(n) 3's between successive 2's.
formula: a(n) = f(n,2,2,2) with f(n,b,c,i) = if n=1 then b else (if c=0 then f(n-1,2,a(i),i+1) else f(n-1,3,c-1,i)). [_Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 25 2009]
a(n) = A080757(n-1) + 1; a(n) = A188068(n) + 2. [_Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 14 2012]

A007539.name: a(n) = first n-fold perfect (or n-multiperfect) number.

A007540.name: Wilson primes: primes p such that (p-1)! == -1 (mod p^2).

A007541.name: Incrementally largest terms in the continued fraction for Pi-2 (cf. A001203).

A007542.name: Successive integers produced by Conway's PRIMEGAME.

A007543.name: Frequency of n-th largest distance in N times N grid, N > n.
formula: a(n) = 2 * n if n is a perfect square, otherwise a(n) = 4 * (n - f(n)) * (ceiling(2 * sqrt(n)) - n + f(n)) where f(n) = floor(floor(2 * sqrt(n))^2 / 4) [from Reddy and Skiena]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 08 2018

A007544.name: Frequency of n-th largest distance in N times N times N grid, N > n.

A007545.name: Number of chess games with n plies (another version).

A007546.name: Number of steps to compute n-th prime in PRIMEGAME (fast version).

A007547.name: Number of steps to compute n-th prime in PRIMEGAME (slow version).

A007548.name: Shifts 3 places left under exponentiation.
formula: E.g.f. A(x) satisfies differential equation A'''(x)=exp(A(x)), A'(0)=1, A''(0)=1, A'''(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 19 2011

A007549.name: Number of increasing rooted connected graphs where every block is a complete graph.

A007550.name: Natural numbers exponentiated twice.
formula: E.g.f.: exp(G(x) - 1) - 1, where G(x) = exp(x*exp(x)) = e.g.f. for A000248; clarified by _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 25 2018
a(n) = sum( k^(n - k) binomial(n,k) bell(k), k = 0..n ). - _Olivier Gérard_, Oct 24 2007

A007551.name: Shifts left when Moebius transformation applied twice.

A007553.name: Logarithmic transform of Fibonacci numbers.
formula: b(n) = b(n-1) - sum(i=1..n-2, b(i)*b(n-1-i)*binomial(n-1,i)), b(0)=1. a(n+1)=abs(b(n)). [_Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 03 2011]
Let e.g.f. E(x)=log(1 + sum(n>=1, Fibonacci(n+1)*x^n/n!)), then g.f. A(x)=x*(1+1/Q(0)), where Q(k)= 1/(x*(k+1)) + 1 + 1/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 07 2013

Let F(x)=log( sum {n = 0..inf} Fibonacci(n+1)*x^n/n!), be the e.g.f., produce the sequence [1,1,-1,-1,7,-5,-85,...], then g.f. A(x)= 1 + x/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + x*(2*k+1) + x^2*(2*k+1)*(2*k+2)/(1 + x*(2*k+2) + x^2*(2*k+2)*(2*k+3)/Q(k+1) ) ; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 23 2013

A007554.name: Unique attractor for (RIGHT then MOBIUS) transform.

A007555.name: Number of standard paths of length n in composition poset.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to n!(c1(n+1+c2)+c2)/((sqrt(2)c2)^n*c1^c1*c2^2) where c1=1+sqrt(2), c2=log(c1).
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - x*(2*k+1) - x^2*(k+1)*(k+2)/2/Q(k+1) ; (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 29 2013

A007556.name: Number of 8-ary trees with n vertices.
formula: a(0) = 1; a(n) = Sum_{i1 + i2 + .. i8 = n - 1} a(i1)*a(i2)*...*a(i8) for n >= 1. - _Robert FERREOL_, Apr 01 2015
a(n) = binomial(8*n, n - 1)/n for n >= 1, a(0) = 1 (from the Lagrange series of the o.g.f. A(x) with its above given implicit equation).
a(n) are special values of Jacobi polynomials, in Maple notation:
A(x)^2 is o.g.f. for A234461; A(x)^3 is o.g.f. for A234462;
A(x)^4 is o.g.f. for A234463; A(x)^5 is o.g.f. for A234464;
A(x)^6 is o.g.f. for A234465; A(x)^7 is o.g.f. for A234466;

A007557.name: Shifts left when inverse Moebius transform applied twice.
formula: a(n+1) = Sum_{d divides n} tau(n/d)*a(d). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jan 24 2003
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x * (1 + Sum_{i>=1} Sum_{j>=1} A(x^(i*j))).

A007558.name: Shifts 2 places left when e.g.f. is squared.
formula: E.g.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = 1 + x + Integral(Integral A(x)^2 dx) dx. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 04 2020

A007559.name: Triple factorial numbers (3*n-2)!!! with leading 1 added.
formula: a(n) = n! *( Sum_{m=1..n} (m/n)*Sum_{k=1..n-m} (binomial(k, n-m-k) * (-1/3)^(n-m-k)*binomial(k+n-1,n-1) + 1 ), n>1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Aug 09 2010
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = a variant of Pascal (1,3) triangle (Cf. A095660); as an infinite square production matrix:
a(n+1) = sum of top row terms of M^n. (End)
a(n) = (-2)^n*Sum_{k=0..n} (3/2)^k*s(n+1,n+1-k), where s(n,k) are the Stirling numbers of the first kind, A048994. - _Mircea Merca_, May 03 2012
G.f.: 1/Q(0) where Q(k) = 1 - x*(3*k+1)/( 1  - x*(3*k+3)/Q(k+1) ); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 21 2013
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k+1)/(x*(3*k+1) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013
E.g.f.: E(0)/2, where E(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k+1)/(x*(3*k+1) + (k+1)/E(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013

Let D(x) = 1/sqrt(1 - 2*x) be the e.g.f. for the sequence of double factorial numbers A001147. Then the e.g.f. A(x) for the triple factorial numbers satisfies D( Integral_{t=0..x} A(t) dt ) = A(x). Cf. A007696 and A008548. - _Peter Bala_, Jan 02 2015

a(n) = sigma[3,1]^{(n)}_n, n >= 0, with the elementary symmetric function of degree n in the n numbers 1, 4, 7, ..., 1+3*(n-1), with sigma[3,1]^{(n)}_0 := 1. See the first formula. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 29 2017
a(n) = (-1)^n / A008544(n), 0 = a(n)*(+3*a(n+1) -a(n+2)) +a(n+1)*a(n+1) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 30 2018
D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +(-3*n+2)*a(n-1)=0, n>=1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 14 2020

A007560.name: Number of planted identity trees where non-root, non-leaf nodes an even distance from root are of degree 2.
formula: Shifts 2 places left under weigh transform.
G.f.: x + x^2 * Product_{n>=1} (1 + x^n)^a(n). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 09 2019

A007561.name: Number of asymmetric rooted connected graphs where every block is a complete graph.
formula: Shifts left when weigh-transform applied twice.

A007562.name: Number of planted trees where non-root, non-leaf nodes an even distance from root are of degree 2.
formula: Shifts left 2 places under Euler transform.
G.f.: x + x^2 / (Product_{k>0} (1 - x^k)^a(k)). - _Michael Somos_, Oct 06 2003
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x) = x + x^2 * exp(A(x) + A(x^2)/2 + A(x^3)/3 + A(x^4)/4 + ...). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jun 11 2021

A007563.name: Number of rooted connected graphs where every block is a complete graph.
formula: Shifts left when Euler transform is applied twice.

A007564.name: Shifts left when INVERT transform applied thrice.
formula: a(0)=1; for n>=1, a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} 3^k*N(n,k) where N(n,k) = (1/n)*binomial(n, k)*binomial(n, k+1) are the Narayana numbers (A001263). - _Benoit Cloitre_, May 24 2003
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A088617(n, k)*3^k*(-2)^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 21 2004
With offset 1: a(1) = 1, a(n) = -2*a(n-1) + 3*Sum_{i=1..n-1} a(i)*a(n-i)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 16 2004
D-finite with recurrence a(n) = (4*(2n-1)*a(n-1) - 4*(n-2)*a(n-2)) / (n+1) for n>=2, a(0) = a(1) = 1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Aug 19 2005
The g.f. of a(n+1) is 1/(1-4x-3x^2/(1-4x-3x^2/(1-4x-3x^2/(1-4x-3x^2.... (continued fraction). (End)
a(0) = 1, for n>=1, 3a(n) = A047891(n). - Aoife Hennessy (aoife.hennessy(AT)gmail.com), Dec 02 2009
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = the production matrix:
G.f.: A(x)= (1+2*x-sqrt(1-8*x+4*x^2))/(6*x)= 1/G(0); G(k)= 1 + 2*x - 3*x/G(k+1); (continued fraction, 1-step ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 05 2012
a(n) = 2^n/sqrt(3)*LegendreP(n,-1,2) for n >= 1, where LegendreP is the associated Legendre function of the first kind, in Maple's notation. - _Robert Israel_, Mar 24 2015

A007565.name: Number of Go games with n moves.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + A048289(n) for n > 0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 24 2016

A007567.name: Knopfmacher expansion of 1/2: a(n+1) = a(n-1)(a(n)+1)-1.
formula: a(n) ~ c^(phi^n), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio and c = 1.438209999512701281674411567... . - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 06 2016

A007568.name: Knopfmacher expansion of 2/3: a(n+1) = a(n-1)(a(n)+1)-1.
formula: a(n) ~ c^(phi^n), where phi = A001622 = (1+sqrt(5))/2 is the golden ratio and c = 1.705023526853159146712304952... . - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 06 2016

A007569.name: Number of nodes in regular n-gon with all diagonals drawn.

A007570.name: a(n) = F(F(n)), where F is a Fibonacci number.

A007571.name: a(n) = largest prime factor of n^n + 1.

A007572.name: Generalization of the golden ratio (expansion of (5-13x)/((1+x)(1-4x))).

A007573.name: Number of asymmetric families of palindromic squares.

A007575.name: Number of stable towers of 2 X 2 LEGO blocks.

A007576.name: Number of solutions to k_1 + 2*k_2 + ... + n*k_n = 0, where k_i are from {-1,0,1}, i=1..n.
formula: Equivalently, the coefficient of x^0 in Product_{k=1..n} (1/x^k + 1 + x^k). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 10 2018

A007577.name: Number of chess games with n plies (another version).

A007578.name: Number of Young tableaux of height <= 7.

A007579.name: Number of Young tableaux of height <= 6.

A007580.name: Number of Young tableaux of height <= 8.

A007581.name: a(n) = (2^n+1)*(2^n+2)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..4} Stirling2(n, k). - Winston Yang (winston(AT)cs.wisc.edu), Aug 23 2000
Binomial transform of 3^n/6 + 1/2 + 0^n/3, i.e., of A007051 with an extra leading 1. a(n) = binomial(2^n+2, 2^n-1)/2^n. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 19 2003
Second binomial transform of A001045(n-1) + 0^n/2. G.f.: (1-5*x+5*x^2)/((1-x)*(1-2*x)*(1-4*x)). - _Paul Barry_, Apr 28 2004

a(n) is the top entry of the vector M^n*[1,1,1,1,0,0,0,...], where M is an infinite bidiagonal matrix with M(r,r)=r, r >= 1, as the main diagonal, M(r,r+1)=1, and the rest zeros. ([1,1,1,...] is a column vector and transposing gives the same in terms of a leftmost column term.) - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 24 2011

A007582.name: a(n) = 2^(n-1)*(1+2^n).
formula: G.f.: (1-3*x)/((1-2*x)*(1-4*x)). C(1+2^n, 2) where C(n, 2) is n-th triangular number A000217.
Binomial transform of A007051. Inverse binomial transform of A081186. - _Paul Barry_, Apr 07 2003
a(n+1) = 4*a(n) - 2^n; see also A049775. a(n) = 2^(n-1)*A000051(n). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 20 2004
Row sums of triangle A134308. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 19 2007
a(n) = StirlingS2(2^n + 1,2^n) = 1 + 2*StirlingS2(n+1,2) + 3*StirlingS2(n+1,3) + 3*StirlingS2(n+1,4) = StirlingS2(n+2,2) + 3(StirlingS2(n+1,3) + StirlingS2(n+1,4)). - _Ross La Haye_, Mar 01 2008
a(n) = StirlingS2(2^n + 1,2^n) = 1 + 2*StirlingS2(n+1,2) + 3*StirlingS2(n+1,3) + 3*StirlingS2(n+1,4) = StirlingS2(n+2,2) + 3(StirlingS2(n+1,3) + StirlingS2(n+1,4)). - _Ross La Haye_, Apr 02 2008
G.f.: Q(0)/2 where Q(k) = 1 + 2^k/(1 - 2*x/(2*x + 2^k/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction ). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 10 2013

A007583.name: a(n) = (2^(2*n + 1) + 1)/3.
formula: a(0) = 1; a(n+1) = a(n) * 4 - 1. - Regis Decamps (decamps(AT)users.sf.net), Feb 04 2004 (correction to lead index by _K. Spage_, Aug 20 2014)
a(n) = Sum_{i + j + k = n; 0 <= i, j, k <= n} (n+k)!/i!/j!/(2*k)!. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 25 2004

a(n) = left and right terms in M^n * [1 1 1] where M = the 3X3 matrix [1 1 1 / 1 3 1 / 1 1 1]. M^n * [1 1 1] = [a(n) A002450(n+1) a(n)] E.g. a(3) = 43 since M^n * [1 1 1] = [43 85 43] = [a(3) A002450(4) a(3)]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 18 2004
a(n) = Sum_{k = -floor(n/3)..floor(n/3)} binomial(2*n, n+3*k)/2. - _Mircea Merca_, Jan 28 2012

a(n) == 2*n + 1 (mod 3). Indeed, from Regis Decamps' formula (Feb 04 2004) we have a(i+1) - a(i) == -1 (mod 3), i= 0, 1, ..., n - 1. Summing, we have a(n) - 1 == -n (mod 3), and the formula follows. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, May 13, 20 2015

A007584.name: 9-gonal (or enneagonal) pyramidal numbers: a(n) = n*(n+1)*(7*n-4)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i = 0..n-1} (n-i)*(7*i+1) for n>0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 10 2014

A007585.name: 10-gonal (or decagonal) pyramidal numbers: a(n) = n*(n + 1)*(8*n - 5)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n-1} (n-i)*(8*i+1), with a(0)=0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 10 2014

A007586.name: 11-gonal (or hendecagonal) pyramidal numbers: n*(n+1)*(3*n-2)/2.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n-1}  (n-i)*(9*i+1), with a(0)=0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 10 2014

A007587.name: 12-gonal (or dodecagonal) pyramidal numbers: n(n+1)(10n-7)/6.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n-1} (n-i)*(10*i+1), with a(0)=0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Feb 10 2014

A007589.name: Dodecahedral surface numbers: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(2)=20, thereafter 2*((3*n-7)^2 + 21).
formula: a(n) = Vertices + Edges*(n-2) + Faces*facenumber(n-3) = 20 + 30(n-2) + 12*A000326(n-3). - _Mitch Harris_, Oct 25 2006

A007590.name: a(n) = floor(n^2/2).
formula: a(n+1) = Sum_{k=1..n} (k + (k mod 2)). Therefore a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} 2*floor(k/2). - _William A. Tedeschi_, Mar 19 2008
a(n) = ceiling((n^2-1)/2) = binomial(n+1, 2) - ceiling(n/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 08 2014, Jun 14 2013
a(n+1) = A014105(n) - A032528(n). - _Richard R. Forberg_, Aug 07 2013

A007591.name: Numbers k such that k^2 + 4 is prime.

A007592.name: Hyperperfect numbers: n = m(sigma(n)-n-1)+1 for some m > 1.

A007594.name: Smallest n-hyperperfect number: m such that m=n(sigma(m)-m-1)+1; or 0 if no such number exists.

A007595.name: a(n) = C_n / 2 if n is even or ( C_n + C_((n-1)/2) ) / 2 if n is odd, where C = Catalan numbers (A000108).

A007598.name: Squared Fibonacci numbers: F(n)^2 where F = A000045.
formula: a(-n) = a(n) for all n in Z.
L.g.f.: 1/5*log((1+3*x+x^2)/(1-6*x+x^2)) = Sum_{n>=0} a(n)/n*x^n; special case of l.g.f. given in A079291. - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 13 2011
Sum_{j=0..2*n} binomial(2*n,j)*a(j) = 5^(n-1)*A005248(n+1) for n >= 1. [P. Stanica; Sum_{j=0..2*n+1} binomial(2*n+1,j)*a(j) = 5^n*A001519(n+1) [P. Stanica]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 16 2006
a(n) = (-1)^k*(Fibonacci(n+k)^2-Fibonacci(k)*Fibonacci(2*n+k)), for any k. - _Gary Detlefs_, Dec 13 2010

a(n) = (((3+sqrt(5))/2)^n + ((3-sqrt(5))/2)^n - 2*(-1)^n)/5; without leading zero we would have a(n) = ((3+sqrt(5))*((3+sqrt(5))/2)^n + (3-sqrt(5))*((3-sqrt(5))/2)^n + 4*(-1)^n)/10. - _Tim Monahan_, Jul 17 2011
E.g.f.: (exp((phi+1)*x) + exp((2-phi)*x) - 2*exp(-x))/5, with the golden section phi:=(1+sqrt(5))/2. From the Binet-de Moivre formula for F(n). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jan 13 2012
Starting with "1" = triangle A059260 * the Fibonacci sequence as a vector. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 06 2012
a(n) = ( T(n,alpha) - T(n,beta) )/(alpha - beta), where alpha = 3/2 and beta = -1 and T(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind.
a(n) = the bottom left entry of the 2 X 2 matrix T(n, M), where M is the 2 X 2 matrix [0, 3/2; 1, 1/2].
a(n) = U(n-1,i/2)*U(n-1,-i/2), where U(n,x) denotes the Chebyshev polynomial of the second kind.
See the remarks in A100047 for the general connection between Chebyshev polynomials and 4th-order linear divisibility sequences. (End)
(F(n)*b(n+2))^2 + (F(n+1)*b(n-1))^2 = F(2*n+1)^3 = A001519(n+1)^3, with b(n) = a(n) + 2*(-1)^n and F(n) = A000045(n) (see Bruckman link). - _Michel Marcus_, Jan 24 2015
a(n) = 1/4*( a(n-2) - a(n-1) - a(n+1) + a(n+2) ). The same recurrence holds for A001254. - _Peter Bala_, Aug 18 2015
4*a(n) = L(n+1)*L(n-1) - F(n+2)*F(n-2), where L = A000032. - _Bruno Berselli_, Sep 27 2017
a(n) = F(n+k)*F(n-k) + (-1)^(n+k)*a(k), for every integer k >= 0. - _Federico Provvedi_, Dec 10 2018

A007600.name: Minimal number of subsets in a separating family for a set of n elements.

A007602.name: Numbers that are divisible by the product of their digits.

A007603.name: Power-sum numbers: let n = a_1 a_2 ... a_k be a k-digit number; n is a power-sum number if there are exponents e_1 ... e_m such that n = Sum_{i=1..m} Sum_{j=1..k} a_j^e_i.

A007604.name: a(n)=a(n-1)+a(n-1- number of odd terms so far).

A007605.name: Sum of digits of n-th prime.

A007606.name: Take 1, skip 2, take 3, etc.
formula: a(n) = n + m*(m+1) where m = floor(sqrt(n-1)). - _Klaus Brockhaus_, Mar 26 2004
a(n+1) = a(n) + if n=k^2 then 2*k+1 else 1; a(1) = 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 13 2009

A007607.name: Skip 1, take 2, skip 3, etc.
formula: a(n) = floor(sqrt(n) + 1/2)^2 + n = A053187(n) + n. - _Ridouane Oudra_, May 04 2019

A007609.name: Values taken by the sigma function A000203, listed with multiplicity and in ascending order.

A007610.name: Sum of n consecutive primes starting at a(n) is prime (or 0 if impossible).

A007611.name: a(n) = n! + 2^n.
formula: a(n) = (n+4) a(n-1) - 4n a(n-2) + (4n-8) a(n-3) with a(0) = 2, a(1) = 3, a(2) = 6. - Dennis S. Kluk (mathemagician(AT)ameritech.net), Feb 12 2006

A007612.name: a(n+1) = a(n) + digital root (A010888) of a(n).
formula: a(1) = 1, a(n+1) = a(n) + a(n) mod 9. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 23 2003
First differences are [1,2,4,8,5,7] repeated. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 15 2009
Lim a(n)/n = 9/2 for n --> oo; A029898(n)=a(n+1)-a(n)=A010888(a(n)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 27 2006

A007614.name: All values attained by the phi(n) function, in ascending order.

A007615.name: Primes with unique period length (the periods are given in A007498).

A007617.name: Values not in range of Euler phi function.

A007618.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + sum of digits of a(n-1), a(1) = 5.
formula: a(n) = A062028(a(n-1)) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Oct 14 2013

A007619.name: Wilson quotients: ((p-1)! + 1)/p where p is the n-th prime.

A007620.name: Numbers n such that every k <= n is a sum of proper divisors of n (for n>1).

A007621.name: Impractical numbers: even abundant numbers (A173490) that are not practical(2) (A007620).

A007622.name: Consider Leibniz's harmonic triangle (A003506) and look at the non-boundary terms. Sequence gives numbers appearing in denominators, sorted.

A007624.name: Numbers m such that the product of proper divisors of m = m^k, k>1.
formula: a(n) = n + O(n/log n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 23 2015

A007625.name: Number of M-sequences from multicomplexes on at most 6 variables with no monomial of degree more than n-1.

A007626.name: Sum of divisors of superabundant numbers (A004394).

A007627.name: Primitive modest numbers.
formula: n = a*10^k + b such that (a, b)=1, n == a (mod b), a < b < 10^k.

A007629.name: Repfigit (REPetitive FIbonacci-like diGIT) numbers (or Keith numbers).

A007631.name: Number of solutions to non-attacking reflecting queens problem.

A007632.name: Numbers that are palindromic in bases 2 and 10.

A007634.name: Numbers n such that n^2 + n + 41 is composite.
formula: a(n) ~ n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Apr 25 2014

A007636.name: Numbers k such that k^2 + k + 17 is composite.

A007638.name: Numbers k such that 3*k^2 - 3*k + 23 is composite.

A007640.name: Numbers k such that 2*k^2 - 2*k + 19 is composite.

A007644.name: Primes not of form | 3^a +- 2^b | where a, b are nonnegative integers.

A007645.name: Generalized cuban primes: primes of the form x^2 + xy + y^2; or primes of the form x^2 + 3*y^2; or primes == 0 or 1 (mod 3).
formula: A007645 UNION A003627 = A000040. - _Juri-Stepan Gerasimov_, Jan 28 2010

A007646.name: Numbers k such that k*4^k + 1 is prime.

A007647.name: Numbers n such that n*10^n + 1 is prime.

A007649.name: Number of set-like molecular species of degree n.
formula: Euler Transform of A007650. Define c(n): c(0)=0. c(k)=a(k), k>0. A007650=MOEBIUSi(c)-c. - _Christian G. Bower_, Feb 23 2006

A007650.name: Number of set-like atomic species of degree n.
formula: Inverse Euler Transform of A007649. Define c(n): c(0)=0. c(k)=A007649(k), k>0. a=MOEBIUSi(c)-c. - _Christian G. Bower_, Feb 23 2006

A007651.name: Describe the previous term! (method B - initial term is 1).

A007653.name: Coefficients of L-series for elliptic curve "37a1": y^2 + y = x^3 - x.
formula: a(n) is multiplicative with a(p^e) = a(p) * a(p^(e-1)) - p * a(p^(e-2)) where a(p) = p+1 - number of solutions of y^2 + y = x^3 - x modulo p including the point at infinity. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 03 2011
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (37 t)) = -37 (t/i)^2 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t).

A007654.name: Numbers k such that the standard deviation of 1,...,k is an integer.

A007655.name: Standard deviation of A007654.
formula: a(n+1) = S(n-1, 14), n>=0, with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. S(-1, x) := 0. See A049310.
Chebyshev's polynomials U(n-2, x) evaluated at x=7.
a(n) = b such that (-1)^n/4*Integral_{x=-Pi/2..Pi/2} (sin((2*n-2)*x))/(2-sin(x)) dx = c+b*log(3). - _Francesco Daddi_, Aug 02 2011

A007656.name: Mass number of the most abundant isotope of the element with atomic number Z = n.

A007657.name: Maximal coefficient in (x + x^2 + x^4 + x^8 + ...)^n.

A007658.name: Numbers n such that (3^n + 1)/4 is prime.

A007659.name: Primes p such that Ramanujan number tau(p) is divisible by p.

A007660.name: a(n) = a(n-1)*a(n-2) + 1 with a(0) = a(1) = 0.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to c^(phi^n) where phi = (1 + sqrt(5))/2 and c = A258113 = 1.1130579759029319... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 26 2003
b(n) = a(n+1) is a divisibility sequence. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 29 2012

A007661.name: Triple factorial numbers a(n) = n!!!, defined by a(n) = n*a(n-3), a(0) = a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2. Sometimes written n!3.
formula: a(n) ~ c * n^(n/3+1/2)/exp(n/3), where c = sqrt(2*Pi/3) if n=3*k, c = sqrt(2*Pi)*3^(1/6) / Gamma(1/3) if n=3*k+1, c = sqrt(2*Pi)*3^(-1/6) / Gamma(2/3) if n=3*k+2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 29 2013
0 = a(n)*(a(n+1) -a(n+4)) +a(n+1)*a(n+3) for all n>=0. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 24 2019

A007662.name: Quadruple factorial numbers n!!!!: a(n) = n*a(n-4).
formula: a(n) ~ c * n^(n/4+1/2)/exp(n/4), where c = sqrt(Pi/2) if n=4*k, c = 2*sqrt(Pi)/Gamma(1/4) if n=4*k+1, c = sqrt(2) if n=4*k+2, c = sqrt(Pi)/Gamma(3/4) if n=4*k+3. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jul 29 2013

A007663.name: Fermat quotients: (2^(p-1)-1)/p, where p=prime(n).
formula: a(n) = 3*A096060(n) for n>2. a(n) = 3*A001045(prime(n)-1)/prime(n) for n>1. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Oct 01 2006

A007664.name: Reve's puzzle: number of moves needed to solve the Towers of Hanoi puzzle with 4 pegs and n disks, according to the Frame-Stewart algorithm.
formula: a(n) = min{ 2 a(k) + 2^(n-k) - 1 ; k < n}, which is always odd. - _M. F. Hasler_, Feb 06 2008
a(n) = sum(2^A003056(i), i=0..n-1). - Daniele Parisse (daniele.parisse(AT)m.eads.net), May 09 2003
a(n) = 1 + (n + A003056(n) - 1 - A003056(n)*(A003056(n) + 1)/2)*2^A003056(n). - Daniele Parisse (daniele.parisse(AT)m.dasa.de), Feb 06 2001

A007666.name: a(n) = smallest number k such that k^n is the sum of n positive n-th powers, or 0 if no solution exists.

A007667.name: The sum of both two and three consecutive squares.

A007668.name: phi(n) divides sigma(n) and sigma(n)/n > sigma(m)/m for all m < n.

A007670.name: Numbers n such that 2^n - 2^((n + 1)/2) + 1 is prime.

A007671.name: Numbers n such that 2^n + 2^(n + 1)/2 + 1 is prime.

A007673.name: Number of coins needed for ApSimon's mints problem.

A007674.name: Numbers n such that n and n+1 are squarefree.
formula: a(n) ~ k*n, where k = 1/A065474. This result is originally due to Carlitz; for the (current) best error term, see Reuss. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 10 2011, expanded Sep 18 2019

A007675.name: Numbers n such that n, n+1 and n+2 are squarefree.
formula: Numbers x such that m(x)*m(x+1)*m(x+2) = 1, where m(w) = abs(mu(w)). - _Labos Elemer_
a(n) ~ cn with c = 7.96895... = 1/A206256. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Mar 05 2013

A007678.name: Number of regions in regular n-gon with all diagonals drawn.
formula: For odd n > 3, a(n) = sumstep {i=5, n, 2, (i-2)*floor(n/2)+(i-4)*ceiling(n/2)+1} + x*(x+1)*(2*x+1)/6*n), where x = (n-5)/2. Simplifying the floor/ceiling components gives the PARI code below. - _Jon Perry_, Jul 08 2003
For odd n, a(n) = (24 - 42*n + 23*n^2 - 6*n^3 + n^4)/24. - _Graeme McRae_, Dec 24 2004
For odd n, binomial transform of [1, 10, 29, 36, 16, 0, 0, 0, ...] = [1, 11, 50, 154, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 02 2011
See the Mma code in A006533 for the explicit Poonen-Rubenstein formula that holds for all n. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jan 23 2020

A007679.name: If n mod 4 = 0 then 2^(n-1)+1 elif n mod 4 = 2 then 2^(n-1)-1 else 2^(n-1).

A007680.name: a(n) = (2n+1)*n!.
formula: This is the binomial mean transform of A000354 (after truncating the first term). See Spivey and Steil (2006). - Michael Z. Spivey (mspivey(AT)ups.edu), Feb 26 2006
G.f.: 1 + x*G(0), where G(k)= 1 + x*(k+1)/(1 - (k+2)/(k+2 + (k+1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 08 2013
a(n-2) = (A208528(n)+A208529(n))/2, for n>=2. - _Luis Manuel Rivera Martínez_, Mar 05 2014
D-finite with recurrence: (-2*n+1)*a(n) +n*(2*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 27 2020
Sum_{n>=0} 1/a(n) = sqrt(Pi)*erfi(1)/2 = A019704 * A099288. - _Amiram Eldar_, Oct 07 2020

A007684.name: Prime(n)*...*prime(a(n)) is the least product of consecutive primes that is non-deficient.
formula: a(n) is the solution to Min{x : Floor[sigma(p#(x)/p#(n-1))/(p#(x)/p#(n-1))=2]}, where p#(w) is the w-th primorial number, the product of first w prime numbers. For a>b, the p#(a)/p#(b)=A000210(a)/A000210(b) quotients are p(b+1)*p(b+2)...p(a) where p(j) is the j-th prime number.

A007685.name: a(n) = Product_{k=1..n} binomial(2*k,k).
formula: a(n) = (2^(n^2 + n - 1/24)*A^(3/2)*Pi^(-n/2 - 1/4)*BarnesG(n + 3/2))/(e^(1/8)*BarnesG(n + 2)), where A is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant (A074962), BarnesG is the Barnes G-function. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Sep 18 2015
a(n) ~ A^(3/2) * 2^(n^2 + n - 7/24) * exp(n/2 - 1/8) / (Pi^((n+1)/2) * n^(n/2 + 3/8)), where A = A074962 is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Apr 16 2016

A007686.name: Prime(n)*...*a(n) is the least product of consecutive primes which is non-deficient.

A007687.name: Number of 4-colorings of cyclic group of order n.

A007688.name: Number of 5-colorings of cyclic group of order n.

A007689.name: a(n) = 2^n + 3^n.
formula: Equals double binomial transform of [2, 1, 1, 1, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Apr 23 2008

If p[i] = Fibonacci(2i-5) and if A is the Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)= det A. - _Milan Janjic_, May 08 2010
a(n) = A001550(n) - 1 = A000079(n) + A000244(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 01 2012

A007690.name: Number of partitions of n in which no part occurs just once.
formula: G.f.: Product_{k>0 is a multiple of 2 or 3} (1/(1-x^k)). - _Christian G. Bower_, Jun 23 2000
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 21 2004
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (864 t)) = 1/6 (t/i)^(-1/2) g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g(t) is the g.f. for A137566. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 26 2008

A007692.name: Numbers that are the sum of 2 nonzero squares in 2 or more ways.

A007693.name: Primes p such that 6*p + 1 is also prime.

A007694.name: Numbers k such that phi(k) divides k.
formula: n/phi(n) is an integer if and only if n = 1 or n = 2^w * 3^u for w > 0 and u >= 0.
n/phi(n) = 3 if and only if phi(n)|n and 3|n. - _Thomas Ordowski_, Nov 03 2014
a(n) is approximately exp(sqrt(2*log(2)*log(3)*n))/sqrt(3/2). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Nov 10 2015

A007696.name: Quartic (or 4-fold) factorial numbers: a(n) = Product_{k = 0..n-1} (4*k + 1).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k = 0..n} (-4)^(n-k) * A048994(n, k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 29 2005
a(n) = (-3)^n * Sum_{k = 0..n} (4/3)^k * s(n+1, n+1-k), where s(n,k) are the Stirling numbers of the first kind, A048994. - _Mircea Merca_, May 03 2012
G.f.: 1/T(0), where T(k) =  1 - x * (4*k + 1)/(1 - x * (4*k + 4)/T(k+1)) (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Mar 19 2013
G.f.: 1 + x/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + x + 2*(2*k - 1)*x - 4*x*(k+1)/Q(k+1) (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 03 2013
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x * (4*k + 1)/(x * (4*k + 1) + 1/G(k+1))) (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 04 2013
0 = a(n) * (4*a(n+1) - a(n+2)) + a(n+1) * a(n+1) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 17 2014

Let T(x) = 1/(1 - 3*x)^(1/3) be the e.g.f. for the sequence of triple factorial numbers A007559. Then the e.g.f. A(x) for the quartic factorial numbers satisfies T(int_{0..x} A(t) dt) = A(x). (Cf. A007559 and A008548.) - _Peter Bala_, Jan 02 2015
a(n) = A264781(4*n+1, n). - _Alois P. Heinz_, Nov 24 2015
D-finite with recurrence: a(n) +(-4*n+3)*a(n-1)=0, n>=1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 14 2020

A007697.name: Smallest odd number expressible in at least n ways as p+2*m^2 where p is 1 or a prime and m >= 0.

A007698.name: a(n) = 22*a(n-1) - 3*a(n-2) + 18*a(n-3) - 11*a(n-4). Deviates from A007699 at the 1403rd term.

A007699.name: Pisot sequence E(10,219): a(n) = nearest integer to a(n-1)^2 / a(n-2), starting 10, 219, ... Deviates from A007698 at 1403rd term.

A007700.name: Numbers n such that n, 2n+1, and 4n+3 all prime.

A007701.name: a(0) = 0; for n > 0, a(n) = n^n*2^((n-1)^2).
formula: a(n) = ((2^((n-1)^2))*Det(Vn(xn[1],...,xn[n])))^2, n >= 1, with the determinant of the Vandermonde matrix Vn with elements (Vn)i,j:= xn[i]^j, i=1..n,j=0..n-1 and xn[i]:=cos((2*i-1)*Pi/(2*n)), i=1..n, are the zeros of the Chebyshev T(n,x) polynomials.
a(n) = ((-1)^(n*(n-1)/2))*(2^((n-1)*(n-2))) * Product_{i=1..n} ((d/dx)T(n,x)|_{x=xn[i]}), n > 0, with the zeros xn[i], i=1..n, given above.

A007702.name: a(n) = prime(n)*...*prime(m), the least product of consecutive primes which is non-deficient.
formula: a(n) = Product_{k = n..A007684(n)} prime(k) = Product_{0 <= i < A107705(n)} prime(n+i). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 15 2017

A007705.name: Number of ways of arranging 2n+1 nonattacking queens on a 2n+1 X 2n+1 toroidal board.

A007706.name: a(n) = 1 + coefficient of x^n in Product_{k>=1} (1-x^k) (essentially the expansion of the Dedekind function eta(x)).
formula: eta(z) = q^(1/24) Product_{m>=1} (1-q^m), q=exp(2 Pi i z).

A007707.name: Prime(n)*...*prime(a(n)) is the least product of consecutive primes which is abundant.

A007708.name: Prime(n)*...*a(n) is the least product of consecutive primes which is abundant.

A007709.name: Number of winning (or reformed) decks at Mousetrap.

A007711.name: Number of unreformed permutations of {1,...,n}.
formula: a(n) = n! - A007709(n). - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 17 2018

A007712.name: Number of once reformable permutations of {1,2,...,n}.

A007713.name: Number of 4-level rooted trees with n leaves.
formula: Euler transform applied thrice to all-1's sequence.

A007714.name: Number of 5-level rooted trees with n leaves.
formula: Euler transform applied 4 times to all-1's sequence.

A007715.name: Number of 5-leaf rooted trees with n levels.

A007716.name: Number of polynomial symmetric functions of matrix of order n under separate row and column permutations.
formula: a(n) is the coefficient of x^n in the cycle index Z(S_n X S_n; x_1, x_2, ...) if we replace x_i with 1+x^i+x^(2*i)+x^(3*i)+x^(4*i)+..., where S_n X S_n is the Cartesian product of symmetric groups S_n of degree n. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 09 2000

A007717.name: Number of symmetric polynomial functions of degree n of a symmetric matrix (of indefinitely large size) under joint row and column permutations. Also number of multigraphs with n edges (allowing loops) on an infinite set of nodes.

A007718.name: Number of independent polynomial invariants of matrix of order n.

A007719.name: Number of independent polynomial invariants of symmetric matrix of order n.

A007720.name: Arises in attempts to apply Engel's `probabilistic abacus' to random walks on infinite square grid.

A007721.name: Number of distinct degree sequences among all connected graphs with n nodes.

A007722.name: Number of graphical partitions of biconnected graphs with n nodes.

A007723.name: Triangle a(n,k) of number of M-sequences read by antidiagonals.
formula: a(p, n) = Sum_{k=-1..n} Lp(n, k) where Lp(n, k) satisfies the recurrence: Lp(n, k) = Sum_{i=k..n} L(p-1, n, i)*L(p, i-1, k-1) for p, n >= 1, k >= 0 with the boundary conditions: Lp(n, n) = Lp(n, -1) = 1 for all p >= 1, n >= -1; L0(n, n) = L0(n, -1) = 1 and L0(n, k) = 0 for k different from -1 or n. - Pab Ter (pabrlos2(AT)yahoo.com), Nov 10 2005

A007724.name: Even minus odd extensions of truncated 3 X 2n grid diagram.

A007725.name: Number of spanning trees of Aztec diamonds of order n.
formula: a(n) ~ Gamma(1/4) * exp(8*G*n^2/Pi) / (Pi^(3/4) * sqrt(n) * 4^n), where G is the Catalan's constant A006752. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 05 2021
a(n) = 4^(2*n-1) * Product_{1<=j,k<=n-1} (4 - 4*cos(j*Pi/(2*n))*cos(k*Pi/(2*n)))*(4 + 4*cos(j*Pi/(2*n))*cos(k*Pi/(2*n))); [Knuth Eq. (8) p. 3]. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Jan 05 2021

A007726.name: Number of spanning trees of quarter Aztec diamonds of order n.
formula: a(n) = Product_{0<j<k<n} (4 - 2*cos(j*Pi/n) - 2*cos(k*Pi/n)) [from Chow]. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jan 20 2018
a(n) ~ sqrt(Gamma(1/4)) * 2^(5/8) * exp(2*G*n^2/Pi) / (Pi^(3/8) * n^(3/4) * 2^(n/2) * (1 + sqrt(2))^n), where G is the Catalan's constant A006752.

A007727.name: Number of 2n-bead black-white strings with n black beads and fundamental period 2n.

A007728.name: 5th binary partition function.
formula: G.f.: Product_{k>=0} (1 - x^(5*2^k))/(1 - x^(2^k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 09 2019

A007729.name: 6th binary partition function.
formula: a(2k) = 2*a(k-1) + a(k); a(2k+1) = 2*a(k) + a(k-1). - _Michael J. Collins_, Dec 25 2018

A007730.name: 7th binary partition function.
formula: G.f.: Product_{k>=0} (1 - x^(7*2^k))/(1 - x^(2^k)). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jul 09 2019

A007731.name: a(n) = a(floor(n/2)) + a(floor(n/3)) + a(floor(n/6)).
formula: From given link, a(n) is asymptotic to c*n where c = 12/log(432) = 1.97744865... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Dec 18 2002

A007732.name: Period of decimal representation of 1/n.
formula: Note that if n=r*s where r is a power of 2 and s is odd then a(n)=a(s). Also if n=r*s where r is a power of 5 and s is not divisible by 5 then a(n) = a(s). So we just need a(n) for n not divisible by 2 or 5. This is the smallest number m such that n divides 10^m - 1; m is a divisor of phi(n), where phi = A000010.
phi(n) = n-1 only if n is prime and since a(n) divides phi(n), a(n) can only equal n-1 if n is prime. - Scott Hemphill (hemphill(AT)alumni.caltech.edu), Nov 23 2006

A007733.name: Period of binary representation of 1/n. Also, multiplicative order of 2 modulo the odd part of n (= A000265(n)).
